Внутригрупповой дизайн

У каждого испытуемого своё смещение, размер эффекта у всех один

rr N_sub <- 30 #number of subjects N_trials <- 10 #number of observations per subject per condition #population parameters sigma <- 5 #trial-by-trial error (common across Ss) intercept_mean <- 5 intercept_sd <- 8 effect_size <- 2 intercept_subj = rnorm(N_sub, intercept_mean, intercept_sd) #iterate over subjects to generate data for each one data <- NULL for(subj in 1:N_sub){ data = rbind( data , data.frame( id = subj , condition = 0 , Y = rnorm(N_trials, intercept_subj[subj], sigma) ) , data.frame( id = subj , condition = 1 , Y = rnorm(N_trials, intercept_subj[subj] + effect_size, sigma) ) ) } data\(id = factor(data\)id) #package the data for stan data_1 = list( nY = nrow(data) , nS = length(unique(data\(id)) , Y = data\)Y , cond = factor_to_contrast(data\(condition) , Subj = as.numeric(data\)id) )

Модель 1

Оценка размера эффекта с учетом индивидуальных смещений

rr model_1 <- ’ data { int nY ; # num trials int nS ; # num subjects int Subj[nY] ; # subjects for each trial vector[nY] cond; # contrast for trial vector[nY] Y ; # outcomes } parameters { real sigma ; #trial-by-trial error real intercept ; #population-level intercept real effect ; #population-level effect real intercept_sd ; #SD of subject-to-subject deviation from the population intercept vector[nS] Sintercept ; #variable to store each subjects intercept } model { #priors on population parameters sigma ~ cauchy(0,20) ; intercept ~ normal(5,10) ; effect ~ normal(0,10) ; intercept_sd ~ cauchy(0,20) ; #assert sampling of subject-level parameters given population parameters Sintercept ~ normal(intercept,intercept_sd) ; #assert sampling of trial-by-trial data given subject-level parameters and sigma for(i in 1:nY){ Y[i] ~ normal(Sintercept[Subj[i]] + effect*cond[i] , sigma) ; } } ’

rr fit_1 <- stan(model_code = model_1, data = data_1)

rr N_sub = 30 #number of subjects N_trials = 10 #number of observations per subject per condition #population parameters sigma = 5 #trial-by-trial error (common across Ss) intercept_mean = 5 intercept_sd = 8 effect_mean = 2 effect_sd = 3 intercept_subj = rnorm(N_sub, intercept_mean, intercept_sd) effect_subj = rnorm(N_sub, effect_mean, effect_sd) #iterate over subjects to generate data for each one data = NULL for(subj in 1:N_sub){ data = rbind( data , data.frame( id = subj , condition = 0 , Y = rnorm(N_trials, intercept_subj[subj], sigma) ) , data.frame( id = subj , condition = 1 , Y = rnorm(N_trials, intercept_subj[subj] + effect_subj[subj], sigma) ) ) } data\(id = factor(data\)id) #package the data for stan data_1 = list( nY = nrow(data) , nS = length(unique(data\(id)) , Y = data\)Y , cond = factor_to_contrast(data\(condition) , Subj = as.numeric(data\)id) )

Модель 2

Оценка размера эффекта с учетом индивидуальных смещений и индивидуального смещения

rr model_1 <- ’ data { int nY ; # num trials int nS ; # num subjects int Subj[nY] ; # subjects for each trial vector[nY] cond; # contrast for trial vector[nY] Y ; # outcomes } parameters { real sigma ; #trial-by-trial error real intercept ; #population-level intercept real effect ; #population-level effect real intercept_sd ; #SD of subject-to-subject deviation from the population intercept real effect_sd ; #SD of subject-to-subject deviation from the population effect vector[nS] Sintercept ; #variable to store each subjects intercept vector[nS] Seffect ; #variable to store each subjects intercept } model { #priors on population parameters sigma ~ cauchy(0,20) ; intercept ~ normal(5,10) ; effect ~ normal(0,10) ; intercept_sd ~ cauchy(0,20) ; effect_sd ~ cauchy(0,20) ; #assert sampling of subject-level parameters given population parameters Sintercept ~ normal(intercept,intercept_sd) ; Seffect ~ normal(effect,effect_sd); #assert sampling of trial-by-trial data given subject-level parameters and sigma for(i in 1:nY){ Y[i] ~ normal(Sintercept[Subj[i]] + Seffect[Subj[i]]*cond[i] , sigma) ; } } ’

rr fit_1 <- stan(model_code = model_1, data = data_1)
